voice_to_text: Uh, there was a point in my life where I was homeless, and there was a point in my life when I couldn't afford food. Same time, obviously. Uh, and you know who fed me the most? Arabs and Arab men. Specifically. The people that treated me with the most respect, the most consistent respect, and the most kindness were Arabs. Specifically Arab men. I knew that if I begged in the fancier white area that I could get to, in the area near the commuter trains, nobody acknowledged I existed. They walked by me, they didn't see me. And if you can't afford to give someone something and you don't wanna make eye contact, whatever. I'm not here to please. How you interact with people. But these are people I knew could give. These are people I would see go in and pull out a lot of money, and I'll be like, hey, can you buy me something? They be like, I don't have money. And it's like, okay, whatever. Like, you don't have to give me anything. But they never would. Like, they rarely would. But I could walk not too far away and go into an Arab neighborhood with Arab restaurants and Arab shops, and I didn't even have to ask. I could walk through the neighborhoods and people would be like, do you need to eat? They never asked me if I was hungry. They never asked me if I had money. Do you need to Eat. And they would feed me and they wouldn't feed me crap either. It wasn't yesterday's bread or a peanut butter and jelly sandwich. It was a heaping to go container of the best foods that they like. But I remember one time this guy said, let me get you some food, you look hungry. And I was like, I'm so hungry. And he brought me food and he brought me an entire picture of water to sit and drink. Cause it was not the best day and I needed a lot of water.

voice_to_text: There's been an update on the California doctor who drove his Tesla off of a 250 foot cliff with his 41 year old wife, seven year old girl and four year old boy inside the vehicle. Dalmaish Patel was charged with three counts of attempted murder after he drove his car off of Devil's Slide and landed on the shore of the Pacific Ocean. But miraculously his wife and children all survived. The father pled not guilty claiming that the Tesla was experiencing tire issues at the time. But his own wife says that's a lie. He was just depressed. He's a doctor. He was going to drive off that cliff and he purposefully did. Now his defense is arguing that he suffered from major depressive disorder and he experienced a psychotic break during the incident. Two doctors testified that he was experiencing hallucinations, hearing footsteps and believe that his children were as teeth. And they just had a hearing on Wednesday saying Patel is now seeking a mental health diversion in the case. If accepted, it means he would be put on a two year treatment plan instead of receiving any jail time. And if he doesn't commit any crimes during that time, all charges against him would be dropped. Prosecutors are completely opposed to this saying that he suffered from schizoaffective disorder, not major depressive disorder with a psychotic feature, therefore the treatment wouldn't work. I'll keep you guys updated as the trial continues, do you guys think He was having a mental health crisis at the time. Or do you think he did it on purpose? Let me know in the comments.

Dermash Patel was charged with three counts of attempted murder after he drove his car off of Devil's Slide and landed on the shore of the Pacific Ocean. But miraculously his wife and children all survived. The father plead not guilty claiming that the Tesla was experiencing tire issues at the time. But his own wife says that's a lie. He was just depressed. He's a doctor. He was going to drive off that cliff and he purposefully did. Now his defense is arguing that he suffered from major depressive disorder and he experienced a psychotic break during the incident. Two doctors testified that he was experiencing hallucinations, hearing footsteps and believe that his children were as teed. And they just had a hearing on Wednesday saying Patel is now seeking a mental health diversion in the case. If accepted, it means he would be put on a two year treatment plan instead of receiving any jail time. And if he doesn't commit any crimes during that time, all charges against him would be dropped. Prosecutors are completely opposed to this saying that he suffered from schizoaffective disorder, not major depressive disorder with a psychotic feature, therefore the treatment wouldn't work. I'll keep you guys updated as the trial continues, do you guys think He was having a mental health crisis at the time. Or do you think he did it on purpose? Let me know in the comments.

voice_to_text: This cat was a mayor of a town and even survived an assassination attempt. This is Stubbs, a cat, and it said that in 1997, residents of a small town in Alaska were so fed up with the candidates running for election that they decided to ride in votes for Stubbs. The local friendly cat later became so popular he ran for the US Senate. Every afternoon, Stubbs went to a nearby restaurant and drink water mixed with catnip out of a wine glass, probably because all of the stress he had from his multiple assassination attempts. Stubbs was one shot by teenagers and recovered, but almost lost his life after being mauled by his opposition, a local dog. Word got out about that. Thousands of people from all around the world started donating money to pay for Stubbs Recovery. He also once fell in a restaurant's deep fryer, but luckily it was switched off and cool at the time. He also accidentally got himself into a garbage truck and hitched a long ride outside the town. Stubbs didn't get much done as mayor, but he became so popular it's estimated he brought in about 30 to 40 tours to the town each day. Stubbs passed away in 2017 and the town appointed the new cat as the next mayor, Denali.

Geobotaglia joins us in studio with greater details and reaction from one City Council member. Geoo Isabelle. The letter specifically requests the Attorney General'd office to investigate if her actions in the body camera footage violates any public official standards and whether her actions, quote, reflect the fair administration of justice of Monroe County. And a quote. Now, all nine members of Rochester City Council signed the letter referring to a situation that took place Monday evening where a Webster police officer says he was trying to pull over District Attorney Dorley on Phillips Road. The officer claims Dorley did not pull over, kept driving and didn't stop until she pulled into her own garage. She then immediately got on the phone with the Webster police chief and argued with the officer in front of her. I sat down with Rochester City Council member Mary Lupien today, who says there are councilmen brothers who feel an investigation wouldn't go far enough. She says the video already shows enough detail and they would welcome a resignation. I would like to see an investigation into what actually did happen with the ticket. You know, she followed Through on her threat to not prosecute it. Um, and it makes me curious, to the cases that she's decided, where her head was at. You know, are there other, um, people that she felt were above the law? Law enforcement, for example?

voice_to_text: Thanks to a deathbed confession, a nearly 24 year old cold case was closed this week when the bodies of a missing girl and her mother were found. Ten year old Natasha Alex Carter and her mother Susan disappeared from their home in Beckley, West Virginia in August 2000. But at first police initially reported that Alex may have been abducted by her mother. In a press release from December 2021 about the case, the FBI Pittsburgh said quote at the time of their disappearance, Susan Carter and Alex's father were having a custody dispute and Alex moved in with her mother and mother's new husband, which it's not confirmed that it was actually her mother's new husband, but they moved in and then not long after that, Susan and Alex disappeared. But while it was initially suspected as a parental abduction by Susan after the two remained missing, an investigation into other possibilities ensued, but unfortunately the case went cold. In 2021, the FBI reopened the cold case and started looking into the man Susan and Alex were living with, Larry Webb, which is of his home. Were done in 2022 and 2023 and they found a bullet embedded in the wall of what was Alex's bedroom. Bullet was tested for DNA and it confirmed that blood on it belonged to Alex. In October 2023, Larry Webb was indicted on first degree murder charges for Alex's death, despite Alex and Susan's bodies never being found due to his deteriorating health. Though Webb was Not arrested until April 12th, 2024, but since then he was being held without bond.
